Everything You’ve Been Looking for in an Online Market Research Platform

Market Explorer offers instant access to in-depth data depicted inside easy to analyze charts, graphs, and tables. Customizable data gathering options and themed reports make Market Explorer the top choice among market research platforms.

Get an instant market overview

  • •

    Quickly analyze any market based on the industry or organic competitors with easy-to-use software and marketing research dashboards.

  • •

    Identify industry leaders by acquisition channels, traffic trends, and audience demographics.

  • •

    View traffic data for all domains in the researched market.

Conduct market share analysis

  • •

    Leverage dynamic market insights software to evaluate any market’s size and benchmark the top competitors.

  • •

    Explore market-wide trends to inform your data-driven marketing strategy.

  • •

    Reveal audience demographics, interests, and social media preferences.

Customize your market research approach

  • •

    Choose from over 100 pre-set business categories for industry-wide analysis in any location worldwide.

  • •

    Create a custom overview with tailor-made insights using a single online market research platform.

  • •

    Explore historical data and track emerging trends as you look toward the future.

Develop smarter marketing strategies with Market Explorer

Semrush .Trends’ all-in-one online market research software.

Frequently Asked Questions

How do we gather data to power our market research software? Do we comply with security and privacy policy?

Market Explorer insights are based on petabytes of clickstream data that comes from multiple proprietary and 3rd party data sources. Semrush’s proprietary AI algorithm accumulates, cleans, and processes the raw data, giving you an accurate view of market data reflecting over million real, but anonymized, internet users. The data is then presented in reports across our market research platform.

Learn more about traffic data in the article How Semrush Turns Traffic Data Into Traffic Intelligence

Market Explorer insights are based on petabytes of clickstream data that comes from multiple proprietary and 3rd party data sources. Semrush’s proprietary AI algorithm accumulates, cleans, and processes the raw data, giving you an accurate view of market data reflecting over million real, but anonymized, internet users. The data is then presented in reports across our market research platform.

Learn more about traffic data in the article How Semrush Turns Traffic Data Into Traffic Intelligence

I know my market competitors, but Market Explorer shows a completely different set of players? Why?

When using the “Find Competitors” option to begin your research with our market study software, the tool automatically compiles a list of competitors. These suggested competitors are based on organic search results. In other words, the tool lists websites your website competes with for organic traffic. If you’d like to create your own customized list of competitors, please use the “Custom List” option on the Market Explorer homepage.

Why do some domains show “n/a” across all of the market explorer reports?

There are two reasons you may be seeing “n/a” in Market Explorer reports:

  1. We didn’t have enough clickstream data to properly analyze the domain and provide you with reliable results.
  2. Traffic to this domain comes from different region.

If the issue is related to the traffic’s region, check the domain in “Market Explorer” and filter by “Location” to pinpoint the traffic’s geographic source.

The estimated size of some markets seems large. Are estimates about market size made by our market insights software accurate?

We use the Total Addressable Market (TAM) and Serviceable Addressable Market (SAM) to calculate market size. These metrics reflect the amount of demand across the analyzed market, not the number of individual consumers. For example, a single consumer might buy a product repeatedly, representing multiple units of demand. Because of this, the market size is often greater than the number of individual consumers within that market.

For more information on how we calculate TAM, SAM, and Market Size, you can check out this article
